About
The Magic Circle Headquarters is home to the world's premier magical society, The Magic Circle. It also houses a theatre, museum and entertainment space. We regularly hold events and open days for the public including History and Mystery at The Magic Circle, At Home with The Magic Circle, Close-up at The Magic Circle, Monday Morning Magic and The Magic Circle Christmas Show. Admission to these events is by advance booking only via our website. The nearest tube stations are Euston Square (2 min walk) and Warren Street (5 minute walk) Note The Magic Circle HQ is not open for casual visits.

    Unique and magical
    This is the inner sanctity for magicians but it is in a rather non-descript building behind Euston Station. There is an amazing circular staircase and museum. The latter contains information and exhibits from well known historical magicians. There is also a small bar but strangely the rooms we saw were devoid of windows. The highlight was an intimate show performed by 4 separate and single magicians and this was exceptional with audience involvement. Overall somewhere to visit if you are able.

  • mire16
    Berlin, Germany5 contributions
    Halloween Show and Spirits Cabinet 2023
    The 2023 Halloween Show was okay: a charming hosts, a couple of magicians, a juggling artist. Nothing to write home about, though, especially since the only female in the programme was scantily dressed and danced around in an LED butterfly costume after appearing magic-assistant-like from another magician's trick, not performing any magic herself. In general, the entire evening might have benefited from a woman's perspective, but the Magic Circle did not seem to have left its patriarchal past in the past. The bar sold reasonably priced cocktails that were light on alcohol and that you could not take into the theatre. This I actually found refreshing, but telling the audience that would have been nice, especially since the seats had not been allocated. Before the performance or in the interval you could visit the museum - a room with famous magician's items and you even got a guide explaining three things to the assembled crowd. The seance with a Victorian inspired Spirits' Cabinet was too clownish for my taste, but a nice nod to the Halloween occasion. All in all, an evening to explore the famous magicians' headquarters and the weird fraternity feeling it projects, but a bit too expensive for a lack of wowing tricks or names.

Superb entertainment in an intimate, historic setting
Nov 2024 Family
I went with my wife and two children for a belated birthday present. Before the show started and during the interval we were treated to a highly knowledgeable and entertaining tour of the building and account of the famous magicians whose artefacts were on display. The show itself consisted of close-up magic by four magicians (two in each half), each of whom was both highly accomplished and also very funny. They all engaged with the audience expertly and the craftsmanship of some of the tricks was breathtaking. You know it can't be what it seems; but the performance is so slick and compelling that it's very hard not to believe it! A warm, friendly atmosphere for an evening spent in the company of people who are masters of their profession - my kids enjoyed it as much as I did, which is not something that happens very often.

Superb.

Fiona L
1 contribution
The best magical entertainment in town, delivered by the country's top magicians
Oct 2024 Friends
Enthralling! I cant recommend Close-Up at The Magic Circle enough. I went last Friday and watched pure magic alchemy performed by four very gifted magicians who are some of the best tricksters in the country.

The line-up changes and on the night I went there were four sensational turns. I was impressed by the variety of their different acts. Most notably is the divine, highly entertaining Alex Sprackling who is a top sleight of hand. Sprackling delivers an incredibly slick act full of sensational card tricks, and banter for that matter! The debonair Adam Bownass must be commended for a series of highly entertaining, very clever scarf tricks and he sports an impressive moustache too! Anyone who has ever tried a Rubiks Cube either successfully, but on the whole unsuccessfully, must watch the brilliant Elijah Ko who drew gasps from the audience, and Wayne Fox is clearly a seasoned veteran trickster whose act features a wide repertoire of extraordinary card tricks and vanishing objects. Each act is introduced by a host, and last Friday we were entertained by the eloquent John Duffett in a manner reminiscent of 1950s CBS chat show host, Ed Sullivan.

All four magicians invited audience members to participate and if you are seated in the front row, its highly likely you will be called upon to pick a card, pick any card!
They are a truly talented crack team of illusionists, and the variety of their very different acts provides a constant buzz of excitement in the intimate cabaret atmosphere. Its no wonder virtually every seat was taken and they received standing ovations.

The acts take place on two floors in the Club Room and the Devant Room (named after the first President of The Magic Circle, David Devant) and the magicians rotate, swapping rooms after the interval.

I recommend the VIP ticket which includes a tour of this wonderful venue beforehand - theres plenty to see, from Tommy Coopers famous fez and Martini bottles to props used by Harry Houdini and Paul Daniels, amongst others. There are some great touches. I particularly love the Victorian posters on the stairwell, in fact every inch of the walls and corners of the rooms are all peppered with images and memorabilia from yesteryears of magic.

The BEST entertainment in town, delivered by the most charismatic magicians par excellence, performed in an Aladdins cave of wonder and marvels. Value for money and a top night out. Get your tickets now. Go! Abracadabra!
Written October 8, 2024

Monday Morning at the Magic Circle
Oct 2024 Friends
Once a month on a Monday morning the Magic Circle have a History of Magic tour which includes two close up magic demonstrations. It is absolutely amazing to see magic performed in this way. The magicians are very professional and are available to speak to the audience after their performances. The tour itself is presented informally and very informative. I have been left wanting to see more and will definitely book for an evening show in the theatre. Do not be fooled by the building it is like a tardis with a magnificent staircase. So worthwhile visiting.

Magic for Everyone - Kids Show Live and an Inclusive Experience
Sep 2024 Family
My family and I (my husband, 9 year old, 4 year old and me) have been to the Kids Show Live a couple of times recently and they have been absolutely outstanding both times. Both magicians - PomPom the Magic Fox and Magic Dave - are masters of their craft, engaging both adults and children across the age groups present with their humour, stage presence, and of course, the kind of high quality magic that one would expect at the home of magic!

The set up is ideal for families, with enough time to get a drink, make a loo stop, and take in some of the fascinating magical history in the Devant room (the plasma ball was a big highlight for our two!)

What was particularly special for us was how far above and beyond the team went for our son, who is autistic. The team were incredibly helpful ahead of the event, and gave clear directions as to where to go and what to expect. No one batted an eyelid when I explained that he might leave partway through, and ensured we had seats at the very back of the theatre for a quick exit if need be. Our son was treated with dignity and care, and he has had two fantastic experiences.

Enormous thanks to the stewards/hosting teams too - Matt, Pete, Kaz, and Andy (so sorry if Ive missed anyone!)

For example, one started telling a woman in the audience about how skilled he was with his hands in a weird long intense monologue. The other performer (Wayne) was incredibly offensive in almost every way possible, saying things like:

When a man in the audience reminded him hed called himself attractive, he said he didnt want that comment from a man (I dont like that)

Called the downstairs audience knuckle draggers and said theyd be licking windows, then did an incredibly offensive impression of a person with a disability

Made a xenophobic comment about Polish people

Mocked gender fluidity

He kept saying is that offensive? I dont care and you cant say that any more can you? - which some of the audience seemed to find funny. I was very close to getting up and leaving but wasnt up for being mocked by him in front of everyone.

Ive really got no idea how someone homophobic, xenophobic, ableist, transphobic and sexist can be allowed to perform like that in 2024 in London. And I think the other performers should really revisit how they interact with the audience and how they might make people feel uncomfortable. Its a massive shame because some of the magic was really good.

The host John and the woman who gave us a tour were both fantastic.
